Project 06: Wrangle and Analyze Data¶

Project Motivation keys¶

Key Points¶

Key points to keep in mind when data wrangling for this project:

  • You only want original ratings (no retweets) that have images. Though there are 5000+ tweets in the dataset, not all are dog ratings and some are retweets.
  • Assessing and cleaning the entire dataset completely would require a lot of time, and is not necessary to practice and demonstrate your skills in data wrangling. Therefore, the requirements of this project are only to assess and clean at least 8 quality issues and at least 2 tidiness issues in this dataset.
  • Cleaning includes merging individual pieces of data according to the rules of tidy data.
  • The fact that the rating numerators are greater than the denominators does not need to be cleaned. This unique rating system is a big part of the popularity of WeRateDogs.
  • You do not need to gather the tweets beyond August 1st, 2017. You can, but note that you won't be able to gather the image predictions for these tweets since you don't have access to the algorithm used.

In [12]:
count = 0
fails_dict = {}
start = timer()
# Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file
with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
    for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
        count += 1
        print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
        try:
            tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
            print("Success")
            json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
            outfile.write('\n')
        except tweepy.TweepError as e:
            print("Fail")
            fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
            pass
end = timer()
print(end - start)
print(fails_dict)

Quality¶

df_all_tweets table

  • id and id_str coloumns don't match. Tweeter developer guide for JSON objects suggest id_str is the correct user ID while id is not. Keep id_str and dropid.- Done
  • display_text_range is stored as a list and is not hashable. It makes it very difficult to use some of the pandas methods on the dataframe. Chnage it to 2 columns with start and finish as integers for futur operation(maybe in ML).-Done

  • display_text-range is a list. there are 23 lines with first item in the list being non-zero. it means that the texts is truncated. once mergerd, instead of relying on text column from df_enhanced, we should use full_text from df_all_tweets. So drop the text column from df_enhanced-Done

  • Tweeter api couldn't download 22 of the tweets probably because those tweets are deleted. Find those and remove from df_enhanced-Done

  • non-null values in the ['in_reply_to_screen_name','in_reply_to_status_id', 'in_reply_to_status_id_str','in_reply_to_user_id','in_reply_to_user_id_str'] columns suggest the tweet was written in reply to another user and is not original. We need to remove them.-Done

    • Once these rows were removed, above columns remain filled with null values and become redundant. remove them. -Done.

  • source column contains an html like tag format. 3 different sources of data is clear. they need to be parsed.

  • created_at is an string object, it must be in timestamp format.-Done
  • there are multiple rows in the Dataframe where a single doge has more than one stage such as doggo and puppo at the same time. These needs to be removed.-Done

df_enhanced table

  • id_str is an object made of strings. Considering id-str is a categorical data, all of them must be string. -Done
  • There are 23 data lines with rating_denominator different than 10. It doesn't follow their rating system. These data must be further looked at after merging and possibly corrected/dropped.-done
  • timestamp is an string object, it must be in timestamp format.-Done
  • all 'None' and 'NaN' values are not Pandas's null values.-Done

df_images table

  • tweet_id is an object made of strings. Considering tweet_id is a categorical data, all of them must be string.-Done

Tidiness¶

  • ['in_reply_to_status_id', 'in_reply_to_user_id', 'source'] columns are duplicated between df_all_tweets and df_enhanced. drop them from df_enhanced and keep df_all_tweets.-Done
  • df_enhanced and df_all_tweets should be merged into one table based on their tweet_id aka is_str. df_all_tweets is downloaded recently so when there is an overlap between columns/data, the data from df_all_tweets should be used.-Done
  • rename id_str to tweet_id to be similar to the other tables for future merge/concat-Done

df_all_tweets table

  • following columns have between 0 to 165 datapoints. No reliable interpretation is possible. Delete them: ['contributors','coordinates','geo','place']-Done

df_enhanced table

  • all of these 4 categorical columns, ['doggo','floofer','pupper','puppo'], can be combined to one categorical column.-Done
  • Drop unnecessary columns of ['doggo','floofer','pupper','puppo'] after combining them-Done

df_all_tweets_clean = df_all_tweets.copy()
df_enhanced_clean = df_enhanced.copy()
df_images_clean = df_images.copy()

Define¶

  • All of these 4 categorical columns: ['doggo','floofer','pupper','puppo'] in 'df_enhanced_clean_None' dataframe can be combined to one categorical column.
  • there are multiple rows in the Dataframe where a single doge has more than one stage such as doggo and puppo at the same time. These needs to be removed.

Define¶

df_all_tweets table

  • display_text_range is stored as a list and is not hashable. It makes it very difficult to use some of the pandas methods on the dataframe. Chnage it to 2 columns with start and finish as integers for futur operation(maybe in ML).

df_enhanced table

  • display_text-range is a list. there are 23 lines with first item in the list being non-zero. it means that the texts is truncated. once mergerd, instead of relying on text column from df_enhanced, we should use full_text from df_all_tweets. So drop the text column from df_enhanced

Code¶

In [63]:
df_enhanced_clean.drop(['text'], axis =1, inplace = True)
In [64]:
temp = df_all_tweets_clean.display_text_range.apply(pd.Series)
temp.rename(columns={0:'display_text_start',1:'display_text_finish',}
            ,inplace=True)
temp = pd.merge(temp, df_all_tweets_clean, right_index = True, left_index = True
                                )
temp.drop(['display_text_range'], axis =1, inplace = True)

Define¶

df_all_tweets table

  • non-null values in the ['in_reply_to_screen_name','in_reply_to_status_id', 'in_reply_to_status_id_str','in_reply_to_user_id','in_reply_to_user_id_str'] columns suggest the tweet was written in reply to another user and is not original. We need to remove them.
  • Once these rows were removed, above columns remain filled with null values and become redundant. remove them.

Code¶

In [67]:
temp = df_all_tweets_clean[df_all_tweets_clean.in_reply_to_screen_name.isnull()].copy()
temp.drop(['in_reply_to_screen_name','in_reply_to_status_id',
                          'in_reply_to_status_id_str','in_reply_to_user_id','in_reply_to_user_id_str'],
                         axis =1, inplace = True)
df_all_tweets_clean = temp.copy()

Define¶

df_enhanced table:

  • There are 23 data lines with rating_denominator different than 10. It doesn't follow their rating system. These data must be further looked at after merging and possibly corrected/dropped.

Code¶

In [69]:
df_enhanced_clean = df_enhanced_clean[df_enhanced_clean.rating_denominator==10]

Define¶

  • df_enhanced and df_all_tweets should be merged into one table based on their tweet_id aka id_str. df_all_tweets is downloaded recently so if there is an overlap between columns/data, the data from df_all_tweets should be used.

  • Tweeter api couldn't download 22 of the tweets probably because those tweets are deleted. Find those and remove from df_enhanced. (This will be don as a part of merge.)

Code¶

In [71]:
tweets_merged = pd.merge(df_all_tweets_clean, df_enhanced_clean, on='tweet_id')

mean_fav_count = int(tweets_merged[tweets_merged.favorite_count!=0]['favorite_count'].mean())

# Lets further focus on the frequency plot of the retweet_count.
# Frequency plot shows a positivly skewed distribution
# it is further confirmed by comparing Mean and Median: Mean > Median
median_retweet_count = int(tweets_merged[tweets_merged.favorite_count!=0]['retweet_count'].median())
mean_retweet_count = int(tweets_merged[tweets_merged.favorite_count!=0]['retweet_count'].mean())
sns.distplot(tweets_merged[tweets_merged.favorite_count!=0]
             ['retweet_count'],bins=30,kde=True).annotate('''Median = {}
Mean = {}'''.format(median_retweet_count, mean_retweet_count),(60000,0.0003))

plt.axvline(x=mean_retweet_count, color='black');

Findings:¶

  • Considering that we have removed those tweets with zero 'like' from the plot, we can still see that majority of tweets have been liked less than 4,000 times(Median of data is 3,934). These may be the fans of the page who follow every post and like it.
  • We can also see that there are tweet with more than 4,000 likes. These were possibly those which went viral and got a lot of attention

  • Similar analysis for retweet_count all the liked suggests messages have been generally retweeted less than 2,000 times. The median of the number of retweets is 1,284. You could say these are active fans who retweet the tweeter feed.

  • the strong positive relationship is even more pronounced here and we have the pearsonian coefficient of 0.93 for it.

In [192]:
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
# the following function uses a single colomn from a dataframe and plots the wordcloud
#In the following function, random_state is set for reproducibility and collocation=False means 
#that if the same word is encountered in collocation with different words,
#it is still considered as one word (to remove duplicates)
def wordcloud(tweets,col):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width=800, height=400,collocations=False,background_color="black",stopwords=stopwords,random_state = 2018,max_words=50).generate(" ".join([i for i in tweets[col]]))
    plt.figure( figsize=(20,10))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.axis("off")
